supposed to watch me.”
She had recognized for the lie it was immediately. Damon had never
really told her to do anything. All of his orders had been filtered down
through the untrustworthy mouthpiece of her mother, who was about as
interested in watching them as she was in anything else.
But Jay had also known that dealing with Nick now would be easier
than dealing with Nick later, when he would be bearing a grudge after her
return alone.
“All right,” she’d sighed. “Come on, toad.”
They had gone to a thrift store downtown called Hidden Marvels
because Jay wasn’t used to having an allowance and was terrified that it
would be taken away if she overspent. “Why aren’t we going to the mall?”
Nick whined. “They have an arcade. This is where old ladies shop.”
“We’re shopping here,” Jay had said, already annoyed. “Don’t touch
anything. If you break it, you have to buy it,” she added, noticing a sign.
